Energy Development, San Miguel, SM: Philippine Stocks Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-04-12T00:55:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-12/energy-development-san-miguel-sm-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 0.3 percent to
4,227.99.  Energy Development Corp. (EDC)  : The  Philippines ’ largest
geothermal company said it paid before schedule 8.1 billion yen
($96 million) of debt, part of an amount owed to Japan
International Cooperation Agency. The stock rose 0.3 percent to
6.78 pesos.  Petron Corp. (PCOR)  : The Philippines’ largest oil
refiner will add 500 service stations this year,  San Miguel
Corp. (SMC)  Chief Financial Officer Ferdinand Constantino said in a
briefing yesterday. Petron, a unit of  San Miguel , decreased 1.1
percent to 14 pesos.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC PM): The Philippines’ biggest food
and beverage maker will use its share from the proceeds of a
$850 million sale of shares and bonds for its infrastructure
ventures and to boost working capital, a stock exchange filing
showed. Shareholder Top Frontier Investment Holdings Inc. will
use its share of the proceeds to repay loans from its own
investors, a filing showed. San Miguel said in a separate
statement that 22 billion pesos ($510 million) from the proceeds
of the share sale will be spent on the infrastructure business.
The stock sank 7.5 percent to 160 pesos.  SM Development Corp. (SMDC)  : Shares of the property
developer were rated “buy” with a 12-month price target at
9.48 pesos each in initial coverage by Carl Sy, a Manila-based
analyst at Deutsche Bank AG. The stock advanced 4.5 percent to
9.35 pesos.  SM Prime Holdings Inc. (SMPH)  : The largest Philippine
shopping mall operator’s stock rating was lowered to “hold”
from “buy” with a 12-month share price estimate at 12.84
pesos, according to Deutsche Bank’s Carl Sy. The stock fell 0.2
percent to 11.98 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
